-  </section>
-
-  <div class="content-layout">
-    <aside class="toc">
-      <h4>On this page</h4>
-      <ul>
-        <li><a href="#what-it-does">What pd watch Does</a></li>
-        <li><a href="#basic-usage">Basic Usage</a></li>
-        <li><a href="#env-vars">Environment Variables</a></li>
-        <li><a href="#real-world">Real-World Pattern</a></li>
-        <li><a href="#reconnect">Auto-Reconnect</a></li>
-        <li><a href="#sdk">SDK Equivalent</a></li>
-      </ul>
-    </aside>
-
-    <article class="article">
-      <p><code style="font-family: var(--font-mono); background: rgba(0,102,204,0.08); padding: 0.15em 0.4em; border-radius: 4px; font-size: 0.9em;">pd watch</code> turns any script into an ambient agent trigger. It opens a persistent SSE connection to a Port Daddy pub/sub channel and executes a shell command on every message — no polling, no cron jobs, no manual wiring.</p>
-
-      <h2 id="what-it-does">What pd watch Does</h2>
-      <p><code>pd watch</code> subscribes to a channel over Server-Sent Events. When a message arrives, it sets environment variables and execs your script. When Port Daddy restarts or the connection drops, <code>pd watch</code> reconnects automatically with exponential backoff.</p>
-
-      <p>This is the "always-on agent" primitive. A watcher is a lightweight persistent process — not a daemon, just a process that runs a script every time something happens. You can have as many watchers as you have scripts.</p>
-
-      <h2 id="basic-usage">Basic Usage</h2>
-      <pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> pd watch build-results --exec <span class="string">'./analyze.sh'</span>
-<span class="output">Watching channel: build-results
-Connected. Waiting for messages...</span>
-
-<span class="comment"># In another terminal, publish a message:</span>
-<span class="prompt">$</span> pd msg build-results publish <span class="string">'{"status":"failed","job":"test-suite"}'</span>
-
-<span class="comment"># Back in the watcher terminal:</span>
-<span class="output">Message received on build-results
-Running: ./analyze.sh
-Exit code: 0</span></code></pre>
-
-      <p>The <code>--exec</code> flag is a shell command string. It can be any executable: a bash script, a Python script, a Node.js process, or even a direct <code>curl</code> call to another service.</p>
-
-      <h2 id="env-vars">Environment Variables</h2>
-      <p>When your script runs, Port Daddy sets these environment variables:</p>
-
-      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Inside your --exec script, these are available:</span>
-<span class="output">PD_CHANNEL=build-results        # Which channel fired
-PD_MESSAGE={"status":"failed"}  # Full JSON message content
-PD_MESSAGE_CONTENT={"status":"failed"}  # Alias for PD_MESSAGE
-PD_TIMESTAMP=2026-03-11T08:23:41.000Z  # ISO 8601 timestamp</span></code></pre>
-
-      <p>Your script can parse <code>PD_MESSAGE</code> with <code>jq</code>, Python's <code>json</code>, or Node's <code>JSON.parse</code>. The message is whatever was published to the channel.</p>
-
-      <pre><code><span class="comment"># analyze.sh — reads PD_MESSAGE, routes to the right handler</span>
-<span class="prompt">#!/bin/bash</span>
-STATUS=$(echo "<span class="string">$PD_MESSAGE</span>" | jq -r .status)
-
-<span class="keyword">if</span> [ "<span class="string">$STATUS</span>" = "failed" ]; then
-  echo <span class="string">"Build failed — filing issue"</span>
-  gh issue create --title <span class="string">"Build failed: $(echo $PD_MESSAGE | jq -r .job)"</span>
-<span class="keyword">fi</span></code></pre>
-
-      <h2 id="real-world">Real-World Pattern: CI Notifier</h2>
-      <p>Here's a full pattern: a CI system publishes build results to a channel, and a watcher agent automatically creates GitHub issues on failures and posts Slack messages on success.</p>
-
-      <pre><code><span class="comment"># Start the watcher (runs forever, reconnects on disconnect)</span>
-<span class="prompt">$</span> pd watch ci-results --exec <span class="string">'./ci-notifier.sh'</span> &
-
-<span class="comment"># ci-notifier.sh</span>
-STATUS=$(echo <span class="string">"$PD_MESSAGE"</span> | jq -r .status)
-BRANCH=$(echo <span class="string">"$PD_MESSAGE"</span> | jq -r .branch)
-JOB=$(echo <span class="string">"$PD_MESSAGE"</span> | jq -r .job)
-
-<span class="keyword">if</span> [ <span class="string">"$STATUS"</span> = "failed" ]; then
-  gh issue create \
-    --title <span class="string">"CI failure: $JOB on $BRANCH"</span> \
-    --body <span class="string">"$PD_MESSAGE"</span>
-<span class="keyword">elif</span> [ <span class="string">"$STATUS"</span> = "passed" ]; then
-  curl -s -X POST <span class="string">"$SLACK_WEBHOOK"</span> \
-    -d <span class="string">"{\"text\":\"Build passed: $BRANCH ($JOB)\"}"</span>
-<span class="keyword">fi</span>
-
-<span class="comment"># From CI, publish results:</span>
-<span class="prompt">$</span> pd msg ci-results publish \
-  <span class="string">'{"status":"failed","job":"test-suite","branch":"feature-auth"}'</span></code></pre>
-
-      <h2 id="reconnect">Auto-Reconnect</h2>
-      <p>The SSE connection will eventually drop — Port Daddy restarts, network blips, macOS wakes from sleep. <code>pd watch</code> handles this automatically:</p>
-
-      <pre><code><span class="output">Watching channel: ci-results
-Connected. Waiting for messages...
-Message received. Running: ./ci-notifier.sh
-
-[Connection lost]
-Reconnecting in 1s...
-Reconnecting in 2s...
-Reconnecting in 4s...
-Connected. Waiting for messages...</span></code></pre>
-
-      <p>Backoff is exponential (1s, 2s, 4s, 8s...) with a maximum delay of 30 seconds. The watcher will keep trying indefinitely until the connection is restored.</p>
-
-      <h2 id="sdk">SDK Equivalent</h2>
-      <pre><code><span class="keyword">import</span> { PortDaddy } <span class="keyword">from</span> <span class="string">'port-daddy'</span>;
-<span class="keyword">import</span> { execSync } <span class="keyword">from</span> <span class="string">'child_process'</span>;
-
-<span class="keyword">const</span> pd = <span class="keyword">new</span> PortDaddy();
-
-<span class="comment">// Watch a channel and handle messages in-process</span>
-<span class="keyword">for await</span> (<span class="keyword">const</span> message <span class="keyword">of</span> pd.watch(<span class="string">'ci-results'</span>)) {
-  <span class="keyword">const</span> data = JSON.parse(message.content);
-  <span class="keyword">if</span> (data.status === <span class="string">'failed'</span>) {
-    <span class="comment">// Run your handler directly in Node.js</span>
-    <span class="keyword">await</span> handleFailure(data);
-  }
-}</code></pre>
